Deriving valuable insights from marketing dataset¶

We are going to use public dataset from Kaggle. Data was uploaded by anonimous XYZ e-commerce company with their own online marketplace.

Online marketplace (or online e-commerce marketplace) is a type of e-commerce website where product or service information is provided by multiple third parties. Online marketplaces are the primary type of multichannel ecommerce and can be a way to streamline the production process.

Key objectives of these analysis:

  1. Calculate retention rates for:
    • different sales channels
    • different order types

Suggest how we can improve retention rates.

Suggest metrics we need to calculate that can prove/disprove our hyposesis.

  1. Identify different customer segments
  2. Compare customer segments and analyse their trends

1. Calculating retention rates¶

Calculation of retention rates for multiple categories is a lengthy process that requires various data manipulations and graph functions. Therefore, to avoid repetetive actions we will define a function plot_retention that will do all the calculations for us.
In [415]:
#function that shows figure object
#since we are working in Jupyter Notebook Figure.show() doesnt work.
def show_figure(fig):

    # create a dummy figure and use its manager to display "fig"  
    dummy = plt.figure()
    new_manager = dummy.canvas.manager
    new_manager.canvas.figure = fig
    fig.set_canvas(new_manager.canvas)

def plot_retention(dataframe, col, orders=20):
    
    #instantiating figure & axis objects
    fig = plt.Figure(figsize=(20,8), dpi=150, facecolor='xkcd:white')
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(1,2,1)
    ax2 = fig.add_subplot(1,2,2)
    
    #creating empty dataframe to concat all df later on
    total = pd.DataFrame()
    
    #Part 1: inetrate over subcategories in specified column
    for subcategory in np.unique(dataframe[col]):
        user_dict={}
        user_list=[]
        
        #Part 2: interate over user ids that belong to specific category
        #and count number of repetitive purchases
        for user in dataframe[dataframe[col]==subcategory]['user_id']:
            if user in user_dict:
                user_dict[user]+=1
            else:
                user_dict[user]=1
            user_list.append(user_dict[user]) #how many repetitive orders each unique customer made
        
        #Part 3: transform created list to dataframe and normalize values
        df = pd.DataFrame(user_list, columns={'order'}).groupby('order')['order'].count()
        df = pd.DataFrame(dict(orders_number=df.index, frequency=df.values))
        
        #limiting final dataframe to specific orders number (def=20)
        df = df[df['orders_number']<=orders]
        
        #calculating retention rate percentage 
        df['percent'] = df['frequency'].divide(df['frequency'].max()/100)
        
        #creating total dataframe that will be used when plotting heatmap (seaborn)
        pre_total = pd.DataFrame()
        pre_total['{}: {}'.format(col, subcategory)] = df['percent']
        total = pd.concat([pre_total, total], axis=1, ignore_index=False)
        
        #Part 4: creating linear plots for retention
        
        #creating ax1 plot
        ax1.plot(df['orders_number'], df['frequency'])
        
        #editing style of ax1 plot
        ax1.set_title('Retention plot for {}s (Number of orders) \n'.format(col, subcategory))
        ax1.set_xlabel('\nNumber of orders per customer')
        ax1.set_ylabel('Number of orders')
        ax1.set_xticks(np.arange(1, orders+1))
        ax1.set_xticklabels(range(1,orders+1))
        ax1.legend(np.unique(dataframe[col]), title='{}s:'.format(col))
        
        #creating ax2 plot
        ax2.plot(df['orders_number'], df['percent'])
        
        #editing style of ax2 plot
        ax2.set_title('Retention plot for {}s (Percent from orders) \n'.format(col, subcategory))
        ax2.set_xlabel('\nNumber of orders per customer')
        ax2.set_ylabel('Percent from first order')
        ax2.set_xticks(np.arange(1, orders+1))
        ax2.set_xticklabels(range(1,orders+1))
        ax2.legend(np.unique(dataframe[col]), title='{}s:'.format(col))

    #showing lineplot of retention rates
    show_figure(fig)
    
    #Part 5: creating heatmap plot using seaborn library
    
    #creating figure and axes objects
    fig2, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,8), dpi=150, facecolor='xkcd:white')
    
    #creating seaborn plot
    sns.heatmap(total.T, square=True, annot=True, cmap = sns.cm.rocket_r, cbar=False, fmt='.1f')
    
    #editing style of heatmap plot
    ax.set_xticks(np.arange(0.5, orders+0.5))
    ax.set_xticklabels(range(1,orders+1))
    plt.title('Heatmap plot for {} retention rate (%)\n'.format(col))
    plt.xlabel('\nRepeated orders')

Above we succesfully defined plot_retention function that plots retention rates of our customers. 

Lets finally start plotting and analysing!

Analysis of retention rates for sales channels¶

According to the top right graph and volume table we can easily see that:

  • Sales channel 2 has the highest amount of orders, but retention rate is the lowest.
  • Sales channel 1 and 4 have great volumes and the highest retention rates.
  • Sales channel 3 has 1.5% from total orders, which is relatively small.

Lets look at channel No.2 in more detail. It is clear from the volume (48% from total) that channel's advertising is effective. However, according to the heatmap, after the first and second purchases it has the highest drop in retention rate. There are 4 possibilities:

  1. Customers are not satisfied with the quality of the product or delivery/waiting time

    In this case, we would need to conduct a small survey specifically for channel 2 buyers after the first order was delivered. Key objective is to find any problems they could encounter, whether it was delivery or quality. As a result try to work out solutions for these problems. Finally, recalculate retention rate after the changes to see if it showed any improvements.

  2. Channel brings mostly one-time buyers

    One-time buyers could be small businesses ordering merchandise for their employees. Those customers may not need our products every month but if we keep sending them marketing emails every couple of months, they may return again. Dataset is relatively small and includes only a 6 month time period, which is probably not enough to measure the size of this customer segment.

  3. Customers quickly lose interest

    Here we can try a few strategies: increase the number of marketing emails sent after the first purchase or conduct A/B testing by changing product recommendation algorithms. In the first case, we would need to recalculate retention rate to measure the effect. In the second case, we would need to compare distributions of purchases for both cases using T-test (to see significance of the effect and exclude randomness), then calculate retention rates to compare both cases to see which is better.

  4. As seen from the table after retention plots, channel uses only manual and sample order types which show the lowest retention rates (check order types retention graphs)

    See recomendations in analysis of order types section below.

Analysis of retention rates for order types¶

According to the top right graph and volume table we can easily see that:

  • External order type has the largest orders volume and the highest retention rate
  • Manual order type has second highest volume and close to external retention rate
  • Sample order type has the highest amount of first time purchases but the lowest total volume and retention rate.

Brief description of 3 order types:

  • Sample order type - orders that are made on our platform. Allows customers to place one-time order before fully starting using the platform and ordering in larger quantities
  • Manual order type - orders that are made on our platform. Allows customers to manually confirm their orders on our platform
  • External order type - orders that come from other platforms that use our marketplace.

We know that manual and sample order types are used only at sales channel 2 and nowhere else (see the first table after retention plots for sales channels). It comes with no surprise that sample order type shows the lowest retention rate since its idea is about one-time purchases, such that customers can try our product and see the quality before ordering in larger amounts. However, manual order type could have a better retention rate and before suggesting any improvements read the following:

According to research firm Baymond Institute the average cart abandonment rate is 69.23%. This abandonment rate indicates the ratio of your website visitors who started to make a booking, but never completed their purchase. The same study also found that an optimized checkout, one that focuses on usability and design, can increase overall website conversion rates by 35.26%.

Therefore, with manual order type we can have the following problems:

  • Customers place orders in baskets and forget about them

    First of all, check how many orders end up in the baskets but never purchased. If there are large numbers of those orders the solution is simple - remind them about placed orders. We should send them an email after an hour of inactivity. After a month since we started, check email response rates and recalculate retention rate to see the effect.

  • Customers find purchase experience unintuitive and therefore lose interest in proceeding with purchase

    Here we should check which pages of our website show the highest leave rate after the customer placed an order. After finding those, we can conduct A/B testing by changing page's template. Finally, compare distributions of purchases using T-test to see significance of the effect (and exclude randomness) and then calculate retention rates to compare both cases to see which is better.

2. Identifying different customer segments¶

In order to better understand our customers and what they prefer we need to perform segmentation analysis. We are going to use RFM segmentation technique which is commonly used in database marketing and direct marketing and has received particular attention in retail and professional services industries.

RFM stands for the three dimensions:

  • Recency – How recently did the customer purchase?
  • Frequency – How often do they purchase?
  • Monetary Value – How much do they spend?

Conducting RFM segmentation:¶

In [421]:
cols = ['user_id', 'date_sent', 'order_id', 'total_gmv']

#convert date_sent column to datetime
marketing['date_sent'] = pd.to_datetime(marketing['date_sent'])

#create date as if we are working with the recent dataset
last_date = marketing['date_sent'].max()+dt.timedelta(days=1)

# Aggregate data on a customer level
rfm = marketing[cols].groupby(['user_id']).agg({'date_sent': lambda x: (last_date - x.max()).days,
                                                'order_id': 'count',
                                                'total_gmv': 'sum'})

# Rename columns for easier interpretation
rfm.rename(columns = {'date_sent': 'Recency',
                      'order_id': 'Frequency',
                      'total_gmv': 'MonetaryValue'}, inplace=True)

#generating quartiles for recency col
r_labels = range(4, 0, -1)
r_quartiles = pd.qcut(rfm['Recency'], 4, labels = r_labels)
rfm['R'] = r_quartiles.values

#generating quartiles for frequency col
f_labels = range(1,5)
f_quartiles = pd.qcut(rfm['Frequency'].rank(method='first'), 4, labels = f_labels)
rfm['F'] = f_quartiles.values

#generating quartiles for monetaryvalue col
m_labels = range(1,5)
m_quartiles = pd.qcut(rfm['MonetaryValue'], 4, labels = m_labels)
rfm['M'] = m_quartiles.values

#defining key RFM metrics
rfm['rfm_segment'] = rfm['R'].astype(str) + rfm['F'].astype(str) + rfm['M'].astype(str)
rfm['rfm_score'] = rfm[['R', 'F', 'M']].sum(axis=1)

Above we have assigned each unique customer to specific segment based on his/her RFM score. Now we will group customers by those segments and compute summary statistics:
In [422]:
score_segmentation = rfm.groupby('rfm_score').agg({'Recency':'mean', 
                                                   'Frequency':'mean', 
                                                   'MonetaryValue':['mean', 'count']}).round(2)

As we can see, created segments are very clear and logical. The higher the rfm_score of the group of customers the lower recency (which is good), higher frequency and higher monetary value. Moreover, number of customers in each segment seems more or less uniformly distributed which is also good.

Reducing number of segments from 9 to 3:¶

We will reduce number of segments for easier further analysis. Moreover, we will name them in an intuitive way:

  • Best performing customers - Gold segment
  • Well performing customers - Silver segment
  • Worst performing customers - Bronze segment
In [423]:
#defining rfm_level function which will rename our segments
def rfm_level(df):
    if df['rfm_score'] >= 10:
        return 'Gold'
    elif ((df['rfm_score'] >= 6) and (df['rfm_score'] < 10)):
        return 'Silver'
    else:
        return 'Bronze'

# Create a new column RFM_Level which is a rename of rfm_score column
rfm['rfm_level'] = rfm.apply(rfm_level, axis=1)

We have reduced number of segments to 3 and named them in and intuitive way. 

Its time for segment analysis!

Last thing to analyse is where each segment comes from and which order type uses.
In [400]:
str_cols=['order_type', 'sales_channel_id']

for col in str_cols:
    df = combined.groupby([col,'rfm_level'])[col].count().unstack(level=1)
    df = df.divide(df.sum()).T
    ax = df.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(10,8))
    
    plt.title('{} by segments'.format(col))
    plt.ylabel('Percent from all cutomers in given segment\n')
    plt.yticks(ticks=[0,0.5,1], labels=['0%', '50%', '100%'], rotation=0)
    plt.ylim(0,1)
    plt.xlabel('Customer segments')
    plt.xticks(rotation=0)
    sns.despine()
    
    plt.show()

According to the first plot, Gold customers mostly use external order type and sometimes manual. Similar tendency for Silver but they prefer sample over manual. Bronze ones mostly use sample and rarely external.

According to the second plot, Gold customers come from three channels 1, 2 and 3. Silver from 1,2. However, Bronze mostly from second one and a few from 1.

Segmentation Summary:¶

If we want to acquire more Gold and Silver customers in the future we should focus on advertising sales channel 1, then 2 and 4. Similar for order types, we should focus on promoting external type first, than manual and sample.
